      "contextIntro": "Bold invests \\$2000 in an account paying $4\\%$ interest per year, compounded annually."
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AASL-P2-T4-Q5",
      "number": 5,
      "section": "A",
      "maximumMark": 8,
      "topic": "functions",
      "skill_tag": "cubic_functions",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Find the coordinates of the two stationary points of the graph of $g$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "$g'(x) = 3x^2 - 12x + 9 = 0$ (GDC or factor)"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = 1$ and $x = 3$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$(1, 6)$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$(3, 2)$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$(1, 6)$ and $(3, 2)$",
          "solution": "$$g'(x) = 3x^2 - 12x + 9 = 3(x - 1)(x - 3) = 0 \\Rightarrow x = 1, 3.$$$$g(1) = 6, \\qquad g(3) = 2.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(expand(diff(x**3 - 6*x**2 + 9*x + 2, x)), 3*x**2 - 12*x + 9)",
            "Eq((x**3 - 6*x**2 + 9*x + 2).subs(x, 1), 6)",
            "Eq((x**3 - 6*x**2 + 9*x + 2).subs(x, 3), 2)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "State the nature of each stationary point.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$(1, 6)$ is a local maximum"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$(3, 2)$ is a local minimum"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$(1, 6)$ maximum; $(3, 2)$ minimum",
          "solution": "The cubic has a positive leading coefficient, so the first stationary point $(1, 6)$ is a local maximum and $(3, 2)$ is a local minimum.",
          "verify": [
            "Eq((x**3 - 6*x**2 + 9*x + 2).subs(x, 1) - (x**3 - 6*x**2 + 9*x + 2).subs(x, 3), 4)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "c",
          "body": "Hence state the number of solutions of the equation $g(x) = 4$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "the line $y = 4$ lies between the minimum $2$ and the maximum $6$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$3$ solutions"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$3$",
          "solution": "Since $2 < 4 < 6$, the horizontal line $y = 4$ cuts the curve three times, so $g(x) = 4$ has $3$ solutions.",
          "verify": [
            "2 < 4",
            "4 < 6"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "The function $g$ is defined by $g(x) = x^3 - 6x^2 + 9x + 2$."
    },
    {
      "source": "IB-AASL-P2-T4-Q6",
      "number": 6,
      "section": "A",
      "maximumMark": 8,
      "topic": "calculus",
      "skill_tag": "integration_area",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Find the $x$-coordinates of the points where the curve meets the $x$-axis.",
          "marks": 3,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "set $4x - x^2 = 0$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x(4 - x) = 0$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = 0$ and $x = 4$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$x = 0$ and $x = 4$",
          "solution": "$$4x - x^2 = x(4 - x) = 0 \\Rightarrow x = 0 \\text{ or } x = 4.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(4*0 - 0**2, 0)",
            "Eq(4*4 - 4**2, 0)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Find the area of the region enclosed between the curve and the $x$-axis.",
          "marks": 5,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "area $= \\displaystyle\\int_0^4 (4x - x^2)\\,dx$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "antiderivative $2x^2 - \\tfrac{x^3}{3}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "evaluate between $0$ and $4$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$32 - \\tfrac{64}{3}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "area $= \\dfrac{32}{3}$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "area $= \\dfrac{32}{3}$",
          "solution": "The curve is above the axis on $[0, 4]$:$$\\int_0^4 (4x - x^2)\\,dx = \\left[2x^2 - \\frac{x^3}{3}\\right]_0^4 = 32 - \\frac{64}{3} = \\frac{32}{3}.$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(integrate(4*x - x**2, (x, 0, 4)), Rational(32, 3))"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "contextIntro": "The curve $y = 4x - x^2$ encloses a region with the $x$-axis."
    },
